segments.text: Today is November the 23rd, and I'm interviewing Dr. Don F. Seaman, professor of interdisciplinary education and also head of that department, has been in Texas A&M since 1971.

We're going to talk a little bit about perceptions and changes that have come about at Texas A&M since you arrived, which was very shortly after the college was born in 1969. Who was responsible primarily for you coming to A&M?
Probably, you mean at the university or elsewhere?
At the university, for coming to me.
Well, Don Clark was the individual who interviewed me and talked to me over the phone and asked me to come for the interview.
And then because of certain circumstances, I had decided not to come.
Then Don was the one who got on the phone and called me back and told me those circumstances had changed, and I agreed to come over the phone once we negotiated salary.
Okay.

And since your arrival at Texas A&M in 1971, what are some of the major changes that you have perceived in, you know, political, sociological, philosophical, whatever, and what do you think caused these major changes?
First was growth.
Okay.
In 1971, when I came, A&M had 14,000 students.
And much of the growth in the 70s was in the College of Education.
This put a lot of pressure on us for space and faculty.
And that caused some change, because I think the nature of the college changed from kind of a balanced college to one of undergraduate teacher education emphasis.
Then I think some new programs, science education was one, adult education and vocational ed, educational technologies are all new programs that started since 71.
So I've seen the influx of a balance of those kinds of things and a mixture.
I think the college was a bit more narrow in scope
In 71, I think the demands of the public for various kinds of programs have caused the college to broaden its scope and maybe its mission.
Wasn't voc ed already in there?
Is that a new program?
I thought vocation had a close way back.
Started in 1971.
What was it before?
Was it called something else, or was there not any vocational training at all?
No, I think industrially it was there.
Over in...
What was it, engineering technology or someplace?
Right, okay.
So there was no vocational education?
Vocational education was created in 1971 through the, what was that act?
EPDA.
Right, I think Dr. Boone mentioned that.
And through a bunch of fellowships that they got in 71.
Okay, so that's relatively new.
Well, then Gronemann was with industrial ed.
Yes.
All of these were part of the other, okay.
Yeah.
Okay.
And, okay, growth is one.
Is there some other?
I could say the broadening of the scope of the college with the various kinds of programs.
What were the major causes for this?
Was it just the demand of people?
I think the college meeting the needs and demands of the public.
To what extent, then, do you feel that the college has been achieving its mission, which is very broadly defined as teaching, research, and service,
What is the balance in those, say, in your area, the emphasis?
I would say in general, the college has been meeting the teaching and service aspect probably more than the research.
One or two departments probably have been meeting all three.
But I'd say the balance has been mostly in teaching and service at this point.
In your own personal, through your time, how do you balance?
I mean, what, for example, time-wise percentage, you know, what percentage of your time do you do teaching service-oriented activity or research?
Well, about 40% to 50% of my time right now is administration.
Oh, OK. Is that true of most department heads?
Oh, I would say so.
It surely is.
And I've got a small department.
The bigger departments, probably it's even more than that.
I don't know.
I teach a course each semester, usually.
101 a semester.
I try to publish somewhat regularly and probably give more time to service than I should, but it's difficult to turn it down.
And are you very active also in organizational things, like your professional organizations?
Not quite as much as I was.
I was president of our national association.
That took an awful lot of time.
For three years, that was a three-year commitment.
But now I've backed off and do sometimes each year.
Is that encouraged within the college to do a lot of professional association?
The dean told me he had just come off being president of the association.
He said take whatever time it takes because it's important and do it.
How do you feel that this tremendous growth that you just talked about has affected the work that you do with students?
Well, our program has gone from nothing in 1971 to about 130, 140 students.
Wow.
And it loads the faculty.
Our off-campus program takes some of our time and effort also, but that is a very good recruiting device and gets some very good quality students that way.
So it does require more time for teaching and service, at least less time for research,
It doesn't have to be that way.
For example, this semester I'm using students in my classes to start collecting some initial data.
They're field testing questionnaires for me that I'm going to use for collecting data in my own research probably this spring.
So that can be done if it's part of the class assignment carries out real well.
I think you can plan and do it.
But we've had two professional journals in our department in the last five years.
And that's a lot of service.
Takes a lot of time, but those kind of things bring a lot of prestige to the university.
A lot of people in my field know where Texas A&M is and who's there that never paid attention to it before.
And I think that's meaningful.
You're talking about the Lifelong Learning Journal and what's the other one?
And the Adult Literacy and Basic Education that Felons and Conte had for about five years before they left.
Those are two of our three journals.
So when you came then, what did you come...
What department were you a part of?
Educational administration.
I was assigned to Ed Ed for three years.
Bob Fellins and I were assigned there for three years.
And I really believe that Dean Hubert felt that once our soft money ran out, that adulthood would probably dry up and blow away.
We wouldn't be here any longer.
But we filled in.
We went out and started working the field.
And at the end of three years, we had a substantial number of students.
And voc ed still had those fellowships and some students.
So we were put together with Ray Perkins, who was then in iEd.
We were all assigned to interdisciplinary ed, and we started functioning like a department.
In what year?
74, fall of 74.
Don Clark was the acting administrator of the department, acting coordinator.
And it was called ID&E from the beginning?
Okay.
It was Ray and Bob and myself who became the 3X.
Then we began to add.
Okay.
And now you have how many faculty?
Well, there are five in adult education and six in educational technology, all in IDED.
Plus, we use faculty outside the department to teach courses and chair committees.
They're not adjunct.
They're just people we use.
Do you have a limit on how many committees your people can chair or what?
How do you handle that?
On doctor level, we try to limit it to 7 to 10.
Masters, we don't have any limitation.
So because you're dealing, you don't have any undergraduate, right?
No.
So because you're dealing with the graduates, this latest influx of students into the college is not having a tremendous impact on your dealing with students, right?
No.
Because you're still going to have the same.
It does because educational technology teaches those service courses.
And it has a big impact because those classes are always full and students are trying to tear down the doors to get in.
It's their last semester before student teaching.
They don't take it now.
It's going to be a delay and all those sob stories.
But they're real.
And I sympathize with them.
But it does have an effect on us.
Do you see any collaboration or much collaboration among departments within the college or outside the college?
I see some.
For example, IDED and EdEd collaborate on off campus in San Antonio, and now IBTE also.
We register together.
We counsel students into each other's programs and each other's departments and classes.
We try to find out where the individual's needs are best met and advise students to go into that department as best we can.
There are a few joint research projects going.
Not many that I know of, not as many as there probably should be.
And there are several proposals that are going to have faculty from different departments on them.
So there's some of that, yes.
But there could always, there could be more.
There could be much more, yes.
What about the College of Education in collaboration with other colleges and universities?
Are you aware of who?
We had two faculty who had a joint research project with Agriculture Economics.
in studying the learning styles of the undergraduate students.
So that went on for about a year.
But that's the only one that I know of.
When I was part-time ag extension, I did something at College of Agriculture.
When were you that?
Oh, from about 1976 to about 1983, I guess.
You were part-time ag extension?
I was quarter-time ag extension.
How did that come about?
They needed some help in their staff development and didn't have enough.
And I had been a member of Ag Extension, so it seemed like a good thing to do.
And did you teach?
Were those classes or things that you did on campus?
Those were non-credit workshops off campus and going out and training field staff in Extension, doing some workshops on campus at state conference.
Did you like that?
Enjoyed it very much.
That's where I got my positive strokes.
Because people didn't have to take those.
They took them because they wanted them.
So if people were there, I knew it was because they liked it.
I have a lot of secrets.
What are your perceptions of how outsiders view the College of Education at Texas A&M?
People within the state who have dealt with it seem to have a pretty high regard for it.

I think some of this, I think much of it comes from the quality of students we're turning out, both undergraduate and graduate, and from some of the things some of the faculty have done in the state, some workshops and conferences and those kinds of things.
I think they've seen some quality there.
Now, outside of the state of Texas, I don't know.
OK. Do you have a vision of what
what the College of Education is going to be in the 21st century and right now on the undergraduate level, especially there's a lot of upheaval and a lot of potential changes.
Is it going to affect your area very much?
I don't know.
One thing I keep hearing about is a move towards certification in adult education.
If that comes about, the form of it and the scope of it may have a direct effect upon us.
What is that?
I have not heard.
Move toward certification.
Certifying adult education teachers and administrators in the state.
They don't have anything right now?
They don't have to be certified at all?
I have fought that since I've been at Texas A&M.
I have seen what form certification takes in other states, and I think it's worthless.
A couple of classes, that doesn't mean anything.
And often the classes they're taking don't do them any good.
So you're against it?
I'm against it unless somebody comes up with something that guarantees it's going to make a better person by certifying them.
But just taking a couple of classes in adult ed doesn't mean anything.
That's what certification is in a lot of states.
If it's something meaningful and useful, yeah, I would support it.
So do you have any idea what's going to happen with the College of Education in the near future?
I think right now we're at the dictates of the legislature and coordinating board and a lot of other entities.
We're kind of being buffeted about.
Instead of being proactive, we're in a state of reactivity right now because it's just the way it is.
Is that the norm in most colleges of education?
They don't have time to be reactive?
I've been in three colleges, student and faculty, and that's the way I've seen it.
Always proactive.
Always reactive.
Reacting to crises.
So your department is still growing, though?
Well, not anymore.
We pretty well put a cap on it.
For the number of faculty we have, we've reached our limit.
And we will not admit probably any more students than we graduate in the future unless we get increased faculty.
Is there a chance that you will get increased?
We've asked for one, but we'll see what the budget does.
So when was this cap?
Was this cap, I mean, is it a formal cap, or is this kind of an understood?
Our admission standards are higher, and we're turning down more applicants.
What about the admission standards?
What are they, and how do they differ from some of the others?
Well, they consist of a combination of experience, graduate record exam scores, GPR, professional commitment, professional goals.
All these are determined by what we call an admissions assessment form that each student must complete.
which includes a VEDA and asking and answering several questions.
Sometimes we'll call them in for an interview, and occasionally we'll find that our department won't serve their goals or professional goals.
What is the GRE requirement right now?
We like to see 450 on each, the verbal and quantitative.
Minimum 450 on each of those.
Analytical has a little meaning for us, but not too much.
Does each department determine their admission standards?
Yes, each department determines its own.
We have a minimum of three years of relevant experience before we'll admit anybody onto the doctor.
Can you talk a little bit about the highlights?
You've been at A&M now for...
Highlights of what?
Of your career there, your years at A&M, something that has happened or that you feel good about.
Included in that can be some of your own contributions as well as insights or anecdotes.
Well, the highlights have been the faculty I've been privileged to work with.
I think we've had some excellent faculty all across the college.
I can name several, but I won't.
I had some wonderful experience with graduate students.
I've seen students come in and go out and assume positions of leadership that I just never would have dreamed possible.
One individual, he was a
A Meek student counselor, school counselor in San Antonio is now a training director in a hard-nosed industry in Houston.
Never would have believed she could have done that, but they love her.
She's just really good.
And some others who are deans and directors and so forth that I think have just made wonderful contributions that make your life very worthwhile.
I think winning the faculty achievement award in continuing education was one of my highlights.
Is that the former students?
Former student association.
I think it was 79.
Just prior to when they raised the award in the amount.
What is it now?
I think it's 4,000 now.
I got 1,000.
Is it that much?
Mm-hmm.
They did it all in one year, which is fascinating.
Hmm.
Let's see.
Some innovations...
I think when we innovate, when we start inquiry day, at least at the beginning, it generates a lot of excitement.
And I like those kinds of things.
This inquiry thing was a big thrust of the inquiry things, right?
Yes.
And did everybody buy into that pretty much, or was it?
I don't think everybody understood it at first.
But I think everybody did it first.
But for some reason, it's kind of waned.
The first couple years we had these were huge crowds.
And even classes turned their students out to come.
For the inquiry day.
Now that doesn't happen anymore.
That's not the same, though.
That's separate from your inquiry within the college where they have the different faculty collaborating on some inquiry groups.
Well, it kind of culminated in inquiry day.
But I don't think the inquiry committees, for example, the inquiry committee on international education
We haven't had a meeting in over a year, and there's not much happening there, and I don't hear too much about some of the other groups meeting much anymore.
Used to be one on the older adults.
I don't hear much about it.
I think the interest has waned or something's happened.
In fact, they're too busy.
I don't know what.
Did your faculty buy it?
Was your faculty supportive of that?
Did they participate when it first came?
Yeah.
We had faculty.
I think every one of our faculty were on one committee or another one.
One of the things that I've heard is that it

gave faculty, because the college had grown so much and people didn't know each other in different departments, that it was strictly for a collegial type, you know, activity to get people to work outside of department lines and just work on interest.
I think it helped.
Was that the goal of, was that the reason that Dean Corrigan had...
Probably part of it.
I think another reason was to get the faculty more active into inquiry.
And I think that had some success, yes.
This has been his emphasis since he came to Texas A&M.
And I think he's right on target with that.
OK, how does that differ from Dean Hubert's leadership?
Can you elaborate a little bit on the contrast between the two and what kinds of emphasis were?
I never saw Dean Hubert making much effort to get the faculty to work interdisciplinary or cross-disciplinary.
I don't think the dean really encouraged faculty to pursue
specific interests or other kinds of things.
You kind of let them go their own way.
And bigger departments and department heads knew what was best within the departments.
So I think that was one difference.
Can you elaborate a little bit more on your, or reminisce a little on working under Dean Huber and what that entailed versus under Dean Corrigan?
What kinds of things were different?
I was only administrator under Dean Huber a little over a year.
Okay.
I didn't get too much from him.
I learned much from him on how to prepare and how to document, do your homework before you ask for things, which I think is very important.
I don't think he shared as much with us of the university problems and university politics and university structure that Dean Corrigan does.
I've learned much of that from Dean Corrigan.
Dean Corrigan
has his department head to meet with him individually once or twice a month.
Dean Hubert never did that, never encouraged that at all.
And that's very helpful, to get to talk to your dean one-on-one regularly.
That's a very good thing to do.
Dean Corrigan has an open door policy.
He tells students that, and they take him up on it.
I think it kind of surprises them when they find out they can walk into his office with an appointment.
They can go in and talk about anything they want to.
And he listens to them and interacts with them.
Dean Hubert did not do that.
I don't think he encouraged that too much.
Did Dean Hubert teach at all?
I don't know.
I think he taught a class, but I'm not sure.
I don't really remember.
When he went on to be chancellor, was there continuity in the office of the dean?
Well, Phil Imbacher was the interim dean, and he had been in the dean's office as assistant or associate
So him maintaining that office, certainly there was continuity.
And that was his purpose.
And his goal was simply maintain it.
There were no new programs or anything like that going on or starting.
But he kept it going, yes.
OK. And any insights or observations that you have made over the years or anecdotes, something that stands out as above particular incident, particular student, or particular
Well, you mentioned one.
You already did mention a student going on to high levels.
I think the biggest thing that I've had to learn is the Aggie way of doing things.
Which is?
I'll give you a couple examples.
When I came to Texas A&M to interview, I decided not to come to A&M because the individual I was going to be working under who had been hired before me
was not an adult educator, and he couldn't make graduate faculty.
And I knew I could.
So I knew he was going to be doing all the work.
And I went back and told my wife, scratch A&M.
But two or three weeks later, I was called and told the other guy had resigned.
He'd found something else to do.
And then I was asked to consider the first position.
We negotiated over the phone.
So when I came to buy a house, the dean told me, OK, we're getting some applications in.
And we're going to look at them for the second person.
And when we decide who it is we think, we'll send it to you and let you take a look at it.
So about a month later, in August, before I came, I got Bob Pelins' beta and a little note that said, here's the guy we hired.
We hope you like him.
Which showed me right away how Aggies do things.
And the other way, I think, is when Dean Hubert became chancellor.
Because he told me personally that when he was called in, he was called the night before the meeting
They wanted to talk to him the next morning, and he thought they were calling him in to get his input as to what the new chancellor ought to be.
When he walked in the next morning, they asked him to be chancellor, and he had no idea they were going to do that.
And he had not applied for the position.
So Aggies have interesting ways of doing things.
Now tell me about, in your department, because I've heard that about somebody that was hired by the dean when actually it's
up to your department?
For example, when you have a vacancy in your department, what is the process that you go through?
And then does the dean have the authority to tell somebody you're hired to be in Don Seaman's department without first going through you?
He has the authority, I guess.
But I've never heard of that happening, at least in our department.
And the procedure is we advertise a position in the Chronicle and send them to the commission professors on a network across the country.
We view the applications, all the faculty do, and we get it down to about two or three.
And then we call at least two people in to interview, make a certain interview with the dean also, with the beta.
And then at the end of those interviews, we take our vote, and then I go up and sit down with the dean and say, here's who we think we want, and here's why.
And to date, he's always concurred.
Do you ever have any student input into the decisions, or do you let them even look at it?
Every applicant has to present a seminar to our students.

And I can tell you an instance, several years ago, in a voc-ed position when I was coordinator, faculty kind of agreed to hire this individual from an institution in Virginia, and he gave a seminar to the students, and the students came in and said, we don't want him.
So we didn't hire him, because the students said they didn't want him.
I figured they're the ones going to have to
We did not hire them.
Do you know what they based that on?
They didn't think he was going to be very conducive to student-faculty relationships.
They asked him some questions.
He either didn't respond or ignored them or gave them the impression he didn't have to respond to students.
And there were no faculty in there.
We purposely did not sit in there.
So we said, hey, if you don't like him, we're not going to hire him.
And we didn't.
How much emphasis do you put on student-faculty relations?
Do you make that a part of your faculty?
It's a very big part of it.
Our students are all adults.
They're usually professionals.
Sometimes I think we give students maybe more attention than we should, because sometimes they take a lot of time.
But they're the heart of the university.
Without students, we wouldn't need faculty or administrators.
And it's the students for whom the institution is going to be known, not the faculty.
ultimately it's the students and who they are and what they are.
And if you don't have good students and treat them fairly and if they don't have good vibes about your institution, you can have the best faculty in the world, it doesn't mean anything.
Does your department rely very much on soft money?
At present, no.
We did at one time, at one time we were very heavy into soft money.
We had, gosh, one year we had about 676 to $700,000.
But not too much now.
Now, this year, we have about 140,000 to 150,000.
But not much.
Do you encourage your faculty to submit proposals?
I do not encourage the adult faculty right now because of the student load.
When you're chairing about 10 doctoral committees and teaching a course or two and that kind of thing, you haven't got time for projects.
And in educational technology, though, they're writing some grants and getting some money, and yes.
Your department has gone through some monumental change, not monumental, but you just inherited a brand new, not a department, what is it, a part of your department or a program?
Yeah, an academic program.
And also, last year you lost two of your faculty at one time to a place in Wisconsin.
Montana.
Montana.
Can you share a little bit about what that created for you and the department or how you were able to keep the continuity and how you've been able to,
to manage these things as department head?
With great difficulty.
The rest of the faculty picked up the load or tried to.
We cut back a little bit in teaching so that we could keep our student advising load going.
But the main thing is that we did not let any students slow down or did not have any student have any setback in their progress.
We kept them going.
We employed a couple of new faculty as soon as we could at the assistant professor level.
One of them has already made graduate faculty and is permitted now to start advising students and the other one is working on it.
So we hired some pretty good people and kept it going.
By graduate faculty, what does that mean?
That means you are permitted to advise graduate students, chair committees.
And that means you've served on some committees that have finished, and you've published, and you've done a few things that are required to do that.
And why is one of your people, or is it the general over the college, about going up for tenure or for promotion or whatnot?
Is that the criteria set by the college?
In most cases, it's seven years.
So you go in at the beginning of your sixth year.
Then if you don't make it, you've got one more year to work to find another position.
